What?  This means that you must have been using exceptions to communicate type-checking information.  That&#x27;s just a terrible way to write Haskell.  Exceptions only have nice semantics when they&#x27;re e.g. thrown in the IO monad.<p><pre><code>    -- No, no, no, no!
    checkValid :: Int -> ()
    checkValid x = if x >= 5
                   then error &quot;Invalid number!&quot;
                   else ()

    -- This works fine.
    checkValid :: Int -> Either String ()
    checkValid x = if x >= 5
                   then fail &quot;Invalid number!&quot;
                   else return ()
</code></pre>
This may sound a bit harsh, but I think you deserved to lose that 10% if you had such a fundamental misunderstanding of &quot;lazy evaluation&quot;.
